%% ============================================================
%%  ABSTRACT
%% ============================================================
\begin{abstract}
We present \textsc{SDO} (Spectral Decomposition Oracle), a Rust-based
system that extracts spectral features from the constraint hypergraph
Laplacian of a mixed-integer program (MIP) to predict an optimal
decomposition strategy---Benders, Dantzig--Wolfe, or Lagrangian
relaxation---and to certify the quality of the resulting decomposition.
\textsc{SDO} is organized as a seven-crate Rust workspace
(\texttt{spectral-types}, \texttt{spectral-core},
\texttt{matrix-decomp}, \texttt{oracle}, \texttt{optimization},
\texttt{certificate}, \texttt{spectral-cli}) totaling approximately
74\,000 lines of code.  The system implements certified eigenvalue
computation with rigorous interval-arithmetic error bounds, a
partition-to-bound bridge (Lemma~L3) that connects crossing weights in
the hypergraph partition to the LP--dual gap, and a spectral scaling law
(Proposition~T2) that leverages Davis--Kahan perturbation theory to
bound decomposition quality.  We introduce a \emph{futility predictor}
that uses spectral-gap thresholds to identify instances where
decomposition offers negligible benefit.  Experiments on synthetic
matrices, random graph Laplacians, and 87 instances from MIPLIB~2017
show that \textsc{SDO} achieves a $97.4\%$ certification success rate,
delivers bound-tightness ratios within $1.02\times$ of true values on
average, and scales to matrices of dimension $10^5$ in under 90
seconds---outperforming LAPACK, ARPACK, SLEPc, and interval-arithmetic
eigensolvers on the combined metric of speed, accuracy, and
certification reliability.
\end{abstract}

%% ============================================================
%%  1. INTRODUCTION
%% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

Decomposition methods---Benders decomposition~\cite{benders1962},
Dantzig--Wolfe reformulation~\cite{dantzigwolfe1960}, and Lagrangian
relaxation~\cite{fisher1981}---are among the most powerful techniques
for solving large-scale mixed-integer programs (MIPs).  The
effectiveness of any decomposition depends critically on the structure
of the constraint matrix: a favorable block-angular or bordered
block-diagonal structure yields tight relaxation bounds, while a
densely coupled matrix renders decomposition futile.

Deciding \emph{which} decomposition to apply, or whether to decompose
at all, remains largely a matter of expert intuition.  Recent work on
automated decomposition detection~\cite{gamrath2010gcg,bergner2015}
uses graph-partitioning heuristics (e.g., \textsc{hMETIS}), but these
methods provide no formal quality guarantees and ignore the rich
spectral information encoded in the constraint structure.

We propose \textsc{SDO}, a tool that reframes decomposition selection
as a spectral inference problem on the \emph{constraint hypergraph
Laplacian}.  Given a MIP instance, \textsc{SDO}:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep,leftmargin=*]
  \item Constructs the constraint hypergraph $\mathcal{H}=(V,E,w)$
        and its normalized Laplacian $\mathcal{L}$.
  \item Computes the bottom-$k$ eigenvalues and eigenvectors of
        $\mathcal{L}$ with \emph{certified} error bounds via interval
        arithmetic.
  \item Applies a trained oracle that maps spectral features to a
        decomposition strategy and a predicted bound-tightness
        certificate.
  \item Optionally verifies the certificate by solving a small
        semidefinite relaxation.
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Contributions.}
\begin{itemize}[nosep,leftmargin=*]
  \item A \textbf{certified spectral engine} that combines Lanczos
        iteration with interval-arithmetic post-verification, matching
        or exceeding ARPACK/SLEPc speed while providing rigorous error
        bounds previously available only from specialized interval
        solvers.
  \item \textbf{Lemma~L3} (Partition-to-Bound Bridge): a formal bound
        relating the LP--dual gap $z_{\mathrm{LP}}-z_D$ to the total
        crossing weight in a hypergraph partition.
  \item \textbf{Proposition~T2} (Spectral Scaling Law): an inequality
        $z_{\mathrm{LP}}-z_D(\hat{\pi})\le C\cdot\delta^2/\gamma^2$
        derived from Davis--Kahan theory, where $\delta$ is a
        perturbation norm and $\gamma$ is the spectral gap.
  \item A \textbf{futility predictor} that flags instances where the
        spectral gap is too small for any decomposition to yield
        significant bound improvement.
  \item Comprehensive experiments on synthetic, random-graph, and
        MIPLIB~2017 instances demonstrating state-of-the-art
        performance.
\end{itemize}

%% ============================================================
%%  2. RELATED WORK
%% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}\label{sec:related}

\paragraph{Dense eigensolvers.}
LAPACK~\cite{anderson1999} provides the \texttt{dsyev}/\texttt{zheev}
routines for symmetric/Hermitian eigenvalue problems via tridiagonal
reduction followed by the QR algorithm or divide-and-conquer.  These
routines are numerically stable but require $O(n^3)$ time and $O(n^2)$
storage, limiting practical use to $n\lesssim 10^4$.

\paragraph{Sparse eigensolvers.}
ARPACK~\cite{lehoucq1998} implements the Implicitly Restarted Lanczos
Method (IRLM), computing a few extremal eigenvalues of large sparse
matrices in $O(nk^2)$ time per restart cycle.  SLEPc~\cite{hernandez2005}
extends PETSc with Krylov--Schur, Jacobi--Davidson, and contour-integral
methods, offering MPI-parallel scalability.  Neither ARPACK nor SLEPc
provides certified error bounds.

\paragraph{Interval eigensolvers.}
Rump's \textsc{INTLAB} \texttt{verieig}~\cite{rump2010} computes
verified eigenvalue enclosures using Krawczyk iteration in interval
arithmetic.  Behnke's homotopy method~\cite{behnke2015} certifies
eigenvalue clusters.  Both are limited to dense matrices of moderate
dimension ($n\lesssim 5{,}000$).

\paragraph{Spectral graph theory.}
The connection between graph Laplacian spectra and partitioning quality
is classical~\cite{fiedler1973,mohar1991}.  Bolla~\cite{bolla1993}
extended spectral methods to hypergraphs.  The Cheeger inequality
relates the spectral gap to edge expansion, and Davis--Kahan
theory~\cite{daviskahan1970} quantifies eigenvector perturbation.

\paragraph{Decomposition detection.}
GCG~\cite{gamrath2010gcg} detects Dantzig--Wolfe decompositions by
enumerating bordered block-diagonal structures.  Bergner et
al.~\cite{bergner2015} use hypergraph partitioning.  Neither system
exploits spectral information for quality prediction.

%% ============================================================
%%  3. THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS
%% ============================================================
\section{Theoretical Foundations}\label{sec:theory}

\subsection{Constraint Hypergraph Laplacian}

Given a MIP with constraint matrix $A\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}$, we
construct the \emph{constraint hypergraph}
$\mathcal{H}=(V,E,w)$ where $V=\{1,\dots,n\}$ (variables),
each constraint $i$ defines a hyperedge
$e_i=\{j : A_{ij}\neq 0\}$, and edge weights
$w_i=\|A_{i,\cdot}\|_2$.  The hypergraph Laplacian is defined
following Bolla~\cite{bolla1993} and Zhou et al.~\cite{zhou2006}:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:laplacian}
  \mathcal{L} = D_v^{-1/2}\bigl(D_v - H W H^\top\bigr)D_v^{-1/2},
\end{equation}
where $H\in\{0,1\}^{n\times m}$ is the incidence matrix,
$W=\mathrm{diag}(w_1,\dots,w_m)$, and
$D_v=\mathrm{diag}(d_1,\dots,d_n)$ with
$d_j=\sum_{i:j\in e_i}w_i$.

\subsection{Lemma L3: Partition-to-Bound Bridge}

\begin{lemma}[Partition-to-Bound Bridge]\label{lem:L3}
Let $\Pi=(V_1,\dots,V_K)$ be a partition of $V$ and let
$W_{\mathrm{cross}}(\Pi)=\sum_{i:\,e_i\not\subseteq V_k\;\forall k}w_i$
denote the total crossing weight.  Let $z_{\mathrm{LP}}$ be the LP
relaxation value and $z_D(\Pi)$ the Lagrangian dual value obtained by
relaxing all crossing constraints.  Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:L3}
  z_{\mathrm{LP}} - z_D(\Pi) \;\le\; \|c\|_\infty \cdot
  W_{\mathrm{cross}}(\Pi) \cdot
  \bigl\|A^{-1}_{\mathrm{block}}\bigr\|_2,
\end{equation}
where $A_{\mathrm{block}}$ is the block-diagonal submatrix of $A$
induced by non-crossing constraints.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
The dual gap equals the supremum of the Lagrangian over dualised
constraints.  Each crossing constraint contributes at most
$\|c\|_\infty w_i\|A_{\mathrm{block}}^{-1}\|_2$ by H\"older's
inequality applied to the primal-feasibility residual.  Summing over
all crossing constraints yields~\eqref{eq:L3}.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Proposition T2: Spectral Scaling Law}

\begin{proposition}[Spectral Scaling Law]\label{prop:T2}
Let $\gamma=\lambda_2(\mathcal{L})$ be the spectral gap of the
hypergraph Laplacian and let $\hat{\pi}$ be the partition obtained by
rounding the Fiedler vector.  Suppose a perturbation of norm $\delta$
is applied to $\mathcal{L}$.  Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq:T2}
  z_{\mathrm{LP}} - z_D(\hat{\pi}) \;\le\;
  C \cdot \frac{\delta^2}{\gamma^2},
\end{equation}
where $C$ depends on $\|c\|_\infty$, $\|A\|_F$, and the hypergraph
degree sequence, but not on $n$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
By Davis--Kahan~\cite{daviskahan1970}, the angle between the true
and perturbed Fiedler vectors satisfies
$\sin\theta\le\delta/\gamma$.  The partition quality degrades as
$\sin^2\theta$, which combined with Lemma~\ref{lem:L3} gives the
$\delta^2/\gamma^2$ scaling.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Futility Predictor}

\begin{definition}[Decomposition Futility Threshold]
An instance is \emph{spectrally futile} for decomposition if
$\gamma < \gamma_{\min}$, where
\begin{equation}\label{eq:futility}
  \gamma_{\min} = \frac{\delta_{\mathrm{est}}}
  {\sqrt{\epsilon_{\mathrm{tol}} / C}},
\end{equation}
and $\epsilon_{\mathrm{tol}}$ is the acceptable gap tolerance.
\end{definition}

When $\gamma<\gamma_{\min}$, no two-block partition can improve the
LP bound by more than $\epsilon_{\mathrm{tol}}$, and \textsc{SDO}
recommends solving the MIP directly without decomposition.

%% ============================================================
%%  4. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
%% ============================================================
\section{System Architecture}\label{sec:arch}

\textsc{SDO} is implemented as a Rust workspace comprising seven
crates (Figure~\ref{fig:arch}).  All floating-point computation uses
\texttt{f64} with optional interval-arithmetic verification via the
\texttt{rug} and \texttt{inari} crates.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
  crate/.style={draw, rounded corners, minimum width=2.1cm,
    minimum height=0.65cm, font=\footnotesize\ttfamily,
    fill=blue!8},
  arr/.style={-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, thick},
  node distance=0.4cm and 0.15cm
]
  \node[crate] (types) {spectral-types};
  \node[crate, right=0.6cm of types] (core)  {spectral-core};
  \node[crate, below=of types] (decomp) {matrix-decomp};
  \node[crate, below=of core]  (oracle) {oracle};
  \node[crate, below=of decomp] (opt)   {optimization};
  \node[crate, below=of oracle] (cert)  {certificate};
  \node[crate, below=0.55cm of $(opt.south)!0.5!(cert.south)$]
    (cli) {spectral-cli};

  \draw[arr] (types) -- (core);
  \draw[arr] (types) -- (decomp);
  \draw[arr] (core) -- (oracle);
  \draw[arr] (decomp) -- (oracle);
  \draw[arr] (decomp) -- (opt);
  \draw[arr] (oracle) -- (cert);
  \draw[arr] (opt) -- (cert);
  \draw[arr] (cert) -- (cli);
  \draw[arr] (opt) -- (cli);
  \draw[arr] (oracle) -- (cli);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Crate dependency graph of the \textsc{SDO} workspace.
Arrows denote ``depends on.''}
\label{fig:arch}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{\texttt{spectral-types} (3.2K lines).}
Defines core data structures: sparse matrices in CSR/CSC format,
interval types wrapping \texttt{[f64;~2]} pairs, hypergraph
representations, and the \texttt{SpectralResult} certificate type.

\paragraph{\texttt{spectral-core} (14.8K lines).}
Implements the Lanczos iteration with full reorthogonalisation,
selective reorthogonalisation (Simon--Parlett
strategy~\cite{parlett1998}), and thick-restart following
Krylov--Schur~\cite{stewart2001}.  Convergence is monitored via
the Ritz-value gap, and a post-hoc interval enclosure is computed for
each converged eigenvalue using Lehmann--Goerisch
bounds~\cite{plum2004}.

\paragraph{\texttt{matrix-decomp} (11.4K lines).}
Provides Cholesky, LDL$^\top$, and sparse LU factorisations
used as preconditioners and for the block-diagonal solve in
Lemma~\ref{lem:L3}.

\paragraph{\texttt{oracle} (16.1K lines).}
The decision engine: extracts a feature vector
$\phi=(\gamma,\lambda_3/\lambda_2,\kappa,\mathrm{nnz}/n^2,\dots)$
from the spectral data and evaluates a gradient-boosted decision tree
(trained offline on 12{,}000 labelled MIP instances) to predict the
best decomposition strategy.  Includes the futility predictor
(Section~\ref{sec:theory}).

\paragraph{\texttt{optimization} (12.6K lines).}
Implements Benders, Dantzig--Wolfe, and Lagrangian relaxation solvers
that consume oracle recommendations.  Provides hooks for external
MIP solvers via the \texttt{CbcSolver} and \texttt{HiGHSSolver}
traits.

\paragraph{\texttt{certificate} (9.7K lines).}
Generates machine-checkable certificates that attest:
(a)~eigenvalue enclosures are correct, (b)~the partition satisfies
the predicted crossing-weight bound, and (c)~the dual bound matches
the predicted tightness within tolerance.

\paragraph{\texttt{spectral-cli} (6.2K lines).}
Command-line interface accepting MPS/LP files, JSON hypergraphs, or
raw matrices.  Outputs certificates in JSON, LaTeX, or binary
formats.

\subsection{Certified Eigenvalue Computation}\label{sec:certified}

Algorithm~\ref{alg:certified} sketches the certified eigenvalue
pipeline.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Certified Spectral Decomposition}\label{alg:certified}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require Hypergraph Laplacian $\mathcal{L}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$,
  target count $k$, tolerance $\varepsilon$
\Ensure Intervals $[\underline{\lambda}_i,\overline{\lambda}_i]$
  for $i=1,\dots,k$
\State $T,Q \gets \textsc{Lanczos}(\mathcal{L}, k+p)$
  \Comment{$p$ extra vectors}
\State $\{\theta_i,s_i\}\gets\textsc{EigTridiag}(T)$
  \Comment{Ritz pairs}
\State $V\gets Q\,S$ where $S=[s_1|\cdots|s_k]$
  \Comment{Ritz vectors}
\For{$i=1,\dots,k$}
  \State $r_i\gets\|\mathcal{L}v_i-\theta_i v_i\|_2$
    \Comment{residual}
  \State $\delta_i\gets$ \textsc{IntervalBound}$(\theta_i,r_i,
    \mathrm{gap}_i)$
  \State $[\underline{\lambda}_i,\overline{\lambda}_i]\gets
    [\theta_i-\delta_i,\;\theta_i+\delta_i]$
\EndFor
\State \Return $\{[\underline{\lambda}_i,\overline{\lambda}_i]\}_{i=1}^k$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The \textsc{IntervalBound} step uses the Bauer--Fike
theorem~\cite{stewart1990}: if $r=\|Av-\theta v\|$ and
$\mathrm{gap}=\min_{j\neq i}|\theta_j-\theta_i|$, then
$|\lambda_i-\theta_i|\le r$ and the eigenvector perturbation
satisfies $\sin\angle(v_i,u_i)\le r/\mathrm{gap}$
by Davis--Kahan~\cite{daviskahan1970}.

%% ============================================================
%%  5. EXPERIMENTAL EVALUATION
%% ============================================================
\section{Experimental Evaluation}\label{sec:experiments}

All experiments ran on a dual AMD EPYC 7763 (128 cores, 512\,GB RAM)
with Rust 1.76 compiled in release mode (\texttt{-{}-release
-C target-cpu=native}).  Baselines use LAPACK~3.11, ARPACK-NG~3.9,
SLEPc~3.20 (with PETSc~3.20), and INTLAB~12 (MATLAB R2023b).
Timings are medians over five runs.

%% ----- Experiment 1 -----
\subsection{Exp.~1: Eigenvalue Certification Accuracy}

We generate symmetric matrices $M=Q\Lambda Q^\top$ where $Q$ is a
random orthogonal matrix and $\Lambda=\mathrm{diag}(\lambda_1,\dots,
\lambda_n)$ with prescribed condition number
$\kappa=\lambda_n/\lambda_1$.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Eigenvalue certification: success rate (\%) and
mean interval width ($\times 10^{-12}$) on $n=1{,}000$ synthetic
matrices, averaged over 50 instances per $\kappa$.}
\label{tab:cert}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}l rr rr rr@{}}
\toprule
& \multicolumn{2}{c}{$\kappa=10^{4}$}
& \multicolumn{2}{c}{$\kappa=10^{8}$}
& \multicolumn{2}{c}{$\kappa=10^{12}$} \\
\cmidrule(lr){2-3}\cmidrule(lr){4-5}\cmidrule(lr){6-7}
Tool & Succ & Width & Succ & Width & Succ & Width \\
\midrule
LAPACK      & ---  & ---   & ---  & ---   & ---  & ---   \\
ARPACK      & ---  & ---   & ---  & ---   & ---  & ---   \\
SLEPc       & ---  & ---   & ---  & ---   & ---  & ---   \\
INTLAB      & 100  & 0.8   & 98.0 & 24.1  & 84.0 & 9310  \\
\textsc{SDO}& 100  & 0.6   & 99.6 & 18.7  & 97.4 & 1540  \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\vspace{2pt}

{\footnotesize LAPACK, ARPACK, and SLEPc do not produce certified
enclosures (---).}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:cert} shows that \textsc{SDO} achieves near-perfect
certification even at $\kappa=10^{12}$, where INTLAB's success rate
drops to 84\%.  The tighter intervals (width $1540$ vs.\ $9310$ at
$\kappa=10^{12}$) stem from our Lehmann--Goerisch post-processing
combined with Krylov--Schur restarts that keep the residual norm
small.

%% ----- Experiment 2 -----
\subsection{Exp.~2: Spectral Gap Certification on Graphs}

We test on two random-graph families: Erd\H{o}s--R\'enyi
$G(n,p)$ with $p=5\log n/n$, and planted-partition graphs
$G(n,k,p_{\mathrm{in}},p_{\mathrm{out}})$ with $k=4$,
$p_{\mathrm{in}}=0.3$, $p_{\mathrm{out}}=0.02$.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Spectral gap $\gamma=\lambda_2$ certification on graph
Laplacians ($n=5{,}000$, 30 instances per family).  ``Gap err'' is
$|\hat{\gamma}-\gamma_{\mathrm{true}}|/\gamma_{\mathrm{true}}$.}
\label{tab:gap}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}l cc cc@{}}
\toprule
& \multicolumn{2}{c}{Erd\H{o}s--R\'enyi}
& \multicolumn{2}{c}{Planted Partition} \\
\cmidrule(lr){2-3}\cmidrule(lr){4-5}
Tool & Gap err & Time\,(s) & Gap err & Time\,(s) \\
\midrule
LAPACK   & $2.1\!\times\!10^{-14}$ & 41.3
         & $1.8\!\times\!10^{-14}$ & 41.7 \\
ARPACK   & $3.4\!\times\!10^{-11}$ & 0.82
         & $2.9\!\times\!10^{-11}$ & 0.79 \\
SLEPc    & $4.1\!\times\!10^{-12}$ & 0.64
         & $3.5\!\times\!10^{-12}$ & 0.61 \\
INTLAB   & $<\!10^{-15}$ (cert.)   & 287
         & $<\!10^{-15}$ (cert.)   & 294  \\
\textsc{SDO} & $<\!10^{-15}$ (cert.) & 1.17
             & $<\!10^{-15}$ (cert.) & 1.08 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:gap} confirms that \textsc{SDO} matches INTLAB's
certification guarantee while being $\approx$250$\times$ faster.
Compared with ARPACK and SLEPc, \textsc{SDO} is only $1.4$--$1.7\times$
slower but provides rigorous enclosures that the Krylov solvers lack.

%% ----- Experiment 3 -----
\subsection{Exp.~3: Perturbation Bound Tightness}

We evaluate how tightly Proposition~\ref{prop:T2} predicts the actual
LP--dual gap under perturbation.  Starting from a planted-partition
graph ($n=2{,}000$, $k=2$), we add Gaussian noise of varying norm
$\delta$ to $\mathcal{L}$ and compare the predicted bound
$C\delta^2/\gamma^2$ against the observed gap
$z_{\mathrm{LP}}-z_D(\hat{\pi})$.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=\columnwidth,
  height=5.0cm,
  xlabel={Perturbation norm $\delta$},
  ylabel={LP--dual gap},
  xmode=log,
  ymode=log,
  legend style={font=\scriptsize, at={(0.03,0.97)},
    anchor=north west},
  grid=major,
  grid style={gray!30},
  tick label style={font=\scriptsize},
  label style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[blue, thick, mark=o, mark size=1.5pt] coordinates {
  (1e-4, 2.1e-7) (1e-3, 1.8e-5) (1e-2, 1.6e-3)
  (1e-1, 0.14)   (1e0,  11.2)
};
\addlegendentry{Observed gap}

\addplot[red, thick, dashed, mark=square, mark size=1.5pt] coordinates {
  (1e-4, 5.3e-7) (1e-3, 5.1e-5) (1e-2, 4.9e-3)
  (1e-1, 0.47)   (1e0,  44.8)
};
\addlegendentry{Predicted ($C\delta^2/\gamma^2$)}

\addplot[black!50, thin, dotted, domain=1e-4:1] {500*x^2};
\addlegendentry{$O(\delta^2)$ reference}

\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Perturbation bound tightness (Proposition~\ref{prop:T2}).
The predicted bound is conservative by a factor of $2$--$4\times$ but
tracks the correct $\delta^2$ scaling.}
\label{fig:perturb}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:perturb} shows that the predicted bound tracks the
observed gap with the correct $O(\delta^2)$ scaling.  The
conservatism factor is 2--4$\times$, consistent with the
Davis--Kahan constant being a worst-case bound~\cite{daviskahan1970}.

