Figure~\ref{fig:scalability} plots wall-clock time against matrix
dimension.  LAPACK exhibits cubic scaling and exhausts memory at
$n=10{,}000$.  INTLAB is two to three orders of magnitude slower than
the sparse solvers.  \textsc{SDO} tracks ARPACK and SLEPc closely
(within 10--20\% overhead from interval verification) while providing
certified bounds.  At $n=100{,}000$, \textsc{SDO} finishes in 87\,s
versus 118\,s for ARPACK and 79\,s for SLEPc---the small SLEPc
advantage reflects its mature MPI-parallel implementation, but SLEPc
provides no certification.

%% ----- Experiment 5 -----
\subsection{Exp.~5: MIPLIB 2017 Decomposition Selection}

We select 87 instances from MIPLIB~2017~\cite{gleixner2021} with known
optimal decomposition strategies (determined by exhaustive comparison
of Benders, Dantzig--Wolfe, and Lagrangian relaxation, each run to a
1-hour time limit with SCIP~8.0).

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Decomposition selection on 87 MIPLIB~2017 instances.
``Acc'' = fraction predicting the best strategy.  ``Gap'' = mean
relative gap $|z_{\mathrm{pred}}-z_{\mathrm{best}}|/|z_{\mathrm{best}}|$.
``Futile'' = instances correctly flagged as not benefiting from
decomposition.}
\label{tab:miplib}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}l ccc@{}}
\toprule
Method & Acc (\%) & Gap (\%) & Futile prec./rec. \\
\midrule
Random baseline       & 33.3 & 18.7 & ---/--- \\
GCG heuristic         & 62.1 & 7.4  & ---/--- \\
hMETIS + SVM          & 71.3 & 4.9  & ---/--- \\
\textsc{SDO} (no cert.)& 82.8 & 2.3 & 0.88/0.81 \\
\textsc{SDO} (full)   & \textbf{85.1} & \textbf{1.9}
                      & \textbf{0.91}/\textbf{0.86} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:miplib} shows that \textsc{SDO} outperforms all
baselines.  The full pipeline (with certified spectral features)
improves over the uncertified variant by 2.3 percentage points in
accuracy, confirming that rigorous eigenvalue enclosures improve
downstream oracle decisions.  The futility predictor correctly
identifies 86\% of instances where no decomposition helps
(22 out of 87 instances), with 91\% precision.

