numerical reliability.

%% ============================================================
%%  6. DISCUSSION
%% ============================================================
\section{Discussion}\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Certification overhead.}
The interval-arithmetic post-verification adds 10--20\% overhead
relative to plain Lanczos iteration.  This is substantially less than
a full interval eigensolver (INTLAB), because \textsc{SDO} performs
the bulk of computation in hardware floating-point and only invokes
interval arithmetic for the final enclosure step.

\paragraph{Oracle accuracy vs.\ feature quality.}
The 2.3\% accuracy gain from certified features (Table~\ref{tab:miplib})
suggests that even small eigenvalue errors can flip the oracle's
decision near strategy boundaries.  This motivates the certified
pipeline even when performance is the primary concern.

\paragraph{Limitations.}
The current futility predictor uses a single-threshold rule; a learned
multi-feature predictor could improve recall.  The oracle's training
set (12K instances) may not generalise to highly specialised MIP
families.  Finally, the current implementation is single-node;
distributed sparse matrix--vector products (as in SLEPc) would extend
scalability beyond $n=10^5$.

%% ============================================================
%%  7. CONCLUSIONS
%% ============================================================
\section{Conclusions}\label{sec:conclusions}

We presented \textsc{SDO}, a spectral decomposition oracle that
combines efficient Krylov eigensolvers with rigorous
interval-arithmetic certification to automate MIP decomposition
selection.  Our theoretical contributions---the Partition-to-Bound
Bridge (Lemma~L3) and the Spectral Scaling Law (Proposition~T2)---provide
formal justification for spectral-based decomposition quality
prediction.  Experiments on synthetic, random-graph, and MIPLIB~2017
benchmarks demonstrate that \textsc{SDO} outperforms existing tools
across certification success rate, bound tightness, computational speed,
scalability, and numerical reliability.

The source code, benchmarks, and all experimental data are available at
\url{https://github.com/anonymous/spectral-decomposition-oracle} (to be
de-anonymised upon acceptance).

